\begin_layout Subsection
Debt Dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exponential model of debt dynamics is very simple, with important outcome.
 The main question is: should we 
\series bold
care
\series default
 about the level of debt we see?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government budget constraint is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{t}+r_{t}D_{t}-T_{t}=D_{t+1}-D_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the key reason that today is different than it was ~10 years ago?
 The real interest rates are 
\series bold
negative
\series default
 (or close to 0).
 Therefore, the cost of financing debt went down dramatically (as long as
 one believes that in the long run he is not going to default).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Primary deficit is the expenditures minus tax revenues: 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{t}-T_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The deficit is financed by increasing the debt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the short / medium run, taxes are assumed to be a fixed portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of the output, and the government expenditure is a fixed portion 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of the GDP.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\alpha-\tau)Y_{t}=D_{t+1}-(1+r_{t})D_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the GDP in the next period by: 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t+1}=(1+g_{t})Y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 For simplicity, assume the primary deficit is 0 (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\tau$
\end_inset

), then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{D_{t+1}}{Y_{t+1}}=\frac{1+r_{t}}{1+g_{t}}\cdot\frac{D_{t}}{Y_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sustainable debt-to-GDP ratio requires 
\begin_inset Formula $g>r$
\end_inset

 in the long-run (pro-growth measures).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming primary deficit of 0, when 
\begin_inset Formula $r>g$
\end_inset

, debt-to-GDP ratio increases.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $g<0$
\end_inset

, primary deficit and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When primary deficit is positive or negative:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{D_{t+1}}{Y_{t+1}}=\frac{\alpha-\tau}{1+g_{t}}+\frac{1+r_{t}}{1+g_{t}}\frac{D_{t}}{Y_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

